sec.p:
The degradable synthetic polymers, which have widely been used as scaffolding materials in bone tissue engineering, are polyesters. Polyesters are characterised by the ester functional groups along their backbones, which are formed via the condensation polymerisation between carboxylic acid group (–COOH) and a hydroxyl group (–OH) on the precursor monomers. Two widely used monomers are lactic acid and glycolic acid. These small precursor molecules are endogenous to the human metabolism. In principle, polyesters can degrade to natural metabolic products through hydrolysis. Saturated poly(α-hydroxy esters) such as poly(lactic acid) (PLA), poly(glycolic acid) (PGA), poly(\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
